{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 08:47:03.765103", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nOverall assessment\\n- Network control-plane (OSPF) appears healthy across core, distribution, and server access segments. All relevant subnets are present in routing tables and adjacencies are established.\\n- Data-plane reachability is asymmetric: host_1_1_1_1 has full end-to-end connectivity to DNS and web servers; host_2_1_1_1 cannot reach any 10.x networks outside its local segment.\\n- DNS service is up and listening on the correct addresses. Name resolution and web access work from host_1_1_1_1.\\n- HTTP on the web servers is reachable on TCP/80, but the apache2 systemd service reports inactive on all web servers (inconsistent state vs. open port).\\n\\nKey findings and evidence\\n\\n1) OSPF control-plane health\\n- Neighbors: OSPF neighbors exist between all expected pairs; interfaces report “Neighbor Count is 1, Adjacent neighbor count is 1” for each link.\\n  • router_core_1/2/3 and distribution/server routers show 2-Way/DROther states on broadcast links with DR/BDR elections, which is expected.\\n- Routing tables:\\n  • Core and distribution routers have OSPF routes to 10.1.1.0/24, 10.2.1.0/24, and 10.200.0.0/24 with appropriate next hops.\\n  • switch_server_access shows 10.200.0.0/24 connected and 10.1.1.0/24, 10.2.1.0/24 learned via OSPF.\\n  • Example (router_core_1): O>* 10.200.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.3 (eth1); O>* 10.1.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.7 (eth2); O>* 10.2.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.1 (eth0).\\n- Conclusion: OSPF is functioning correctly; no control-plane anomaly detected.\\n\\n2) Data-plane reachability checks\\n- From host_1_1_1_1 (10.1.1.2/24):\\n  • Ping gateway 10.1.1.1: OK.\\n  • Ping DNS 10.200.0.2: OK (rtt ~2 ms).\\n  • Ping web_server_0 10.200.0.3: OK (rtt ~3 ms).\\n  • curl http://web0.local: name lookup and HTTP fetch succeed quickly (total ~11–26 ms).\\n- From switch_dist_1_1 and switch_dist_2_1:\\n  • Pings to 10.200.0.2 and 10.200.0.3: OK from both devices.\\n- From router_core_1 to 10.200.0.2: OK.\\n- From host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.2):\\n  • Ping gateway 10.2.1.1: OK.\\n  • Ping DNS 10.200.0.2: Fails with “From 10.2.1.2 Destination Host Unreachable”.\\n  • Ping web_server_0 10.200.0.3: Fails with “From 10.2.1.2 Destination Host Unreachable”.\\n  • curl http://web0.local: fails/timeouts (total ~4–5 s; no name lookup/connection progress), consistent with DNS unreachability and no HTTP reachability.\\n\\n3) Host_2_1_1_1 IP configuration anomaly (root cause of its reachability issues)\\n- IP configuration on host_2_1_1_1:\\n  • ip addr: inet 10.2.1.2/8 on eth0 (note incorrect /8 mask).\\n  • ip route: kernel route 10.0.0.0/8 dev eth0 scope link; default via 10.2.1.1.\\n  • ARP table: incomplete entries for 10.200.0.2 and 10.200.0.3; resolved MAC for 10.2.1.1.\\n- Effect:\\n  • With /8, the host believes 10.200.0.0/24 is on-link and tries ARP directly for 10.200.0.2/10.200.0.3 instead of sending to the default gateway 10.2.1.1. ARP fails (no L2 adjacency), leading the host itself (10.2.1.2) to emit “Destination Host Unreachable”.\\n  • This explains both DNS failure (cannot reach 10.200.0.2) and HTTP failure (cannot reach 10.200.0.3, nor resolve web0.local).\\n- Localization: Fault is on endpoint host_2_1_1_1; the rest of the network forwards 10.2.1.0/24 ↔ 10.200.0.0/24 properly.\\n\\n4) DNS service status\\n- dns_server named:\\n  • systemctl: active (running).\\n  • netstat: listening on 10.200.0.2:53 (TCP/UDP) and 127.0.0.1:53.\\n  • Hosts’ resolv.conf: both point to nameserver 10.200.0.2.\\n- Name resolution works from host_1_1_1_1 (curl timings show non-zero namelookup), fails from host_2_1_1_1 due to IP reachability issue (not a DNS server fault).\\n\\n5) Web server service status\\n- On all web_server_[0-3]:\\n  • systemctl status apache2: inactive (dead).\\n  • netstat -tuln: TCP 0.0.0.0:80 is LISTENING on each host.\\n- Observation: There is an HTTP listener on port 80, but apache2 service via systemd is inactive. Either a different HTTP daemon is running, or apache is present but not managed via systemd under the apache2 unit name. Despite this, HTTP for web0.local is reachable from host_1_1_1_1.\\n\\nConclusions\\n\\n- Anomaly detected: host_2_1_1_1 is misconfigured with a /8 netmask (10.2.1.2/8). This causes the host to treat all 10.0.0.0/8 destinations (including 10.200.0.0/24) as on-link, resulting in failed ARP, ICMP “Destination Host Unreachable” from 10.2.1.2, and inability to reach DNS and web servers. This is the root cause of host_2_1_1_1’s end-to-end failure.\\n- Network infrastructure (OSPF, routing between core/distribution/server access) is operating normally and carries traffic between 10.1.1.0/24 and 10.200.0.0/24 correctly.\\n- DNS server is healthy and reachable from correctly configured segments.\\n- Side finding: apache2 systemd unit is inactive on all web servers despite TCP/80 being open; HTTP service is still available on web_server_0 at least, but the daemon/service alignment is inconsistent with the “Apache web servers” description., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='471b67c7-baf9-4d7d-a7c3-80fa738ad955'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
